  "prompt": "Does my H1B visa transfer impact my spouse's H4 visa?",
  "response": "When your H1B visa is transferred to a new employer, it can have implications for your spouse's H4 visa. Here\u2019s a step-by-step explanation of what typically happens:\n\n1. **H1B Transfer Process**: When you apply for an H1B transfer, your new employer will file a new petition (Form I-129) with USCIS. Your current H1B status remains valid during the adjudication process, thanks to the portability provision (assuming you have maintained lawful status).\n\n2. **H4 Visa Dependency**: Your spouse's H4 visa is dependent on your valid H1B status. As long as your H1B remains valid (even during the transfer process), your spouse's H4 status is generally secure.\n\n3. **H4 Visa and I-539 Form**: If your H1B transfer is approved, your spouse will need to file Form I-539 to extend or change their nonimmigrant status to continue as an H4 dependent. This should be done concurrently with your H1B transfer if their current H4 status is nearing expiration.\n\n4. **Employment Authorization Document (EAD)**: If your spouse has an H4 EAD, they should be aware that the validity of their EAD is tied to your H1B status. They may need to apply for a new EAD if their current one is set to expire soon after your H1B transfer approval.\n\n5. **Travel Considerations**: If your spouse plans to travel outside the U.S. during the H1B transfer process, they should wait until your H1B transfer is approved and their H4 status is secured. Otherwise, they might face difficulties re-entering the U.S.\n\n6. **Legal Advice**: It's always a good idea to consult with an immigration attorney to ensure all paperwork is filed correctly and to address any specific concerns related to your situation.\n\nIn summary, your H1B visa transfer does impact your spouse's H4 visa, but as long as the transfer process is handled correctly and in a timely manner, your spouse's H4 status should remain valid.",
